1. Load and clean data¶

So we need to read the data, name columns and take mean over Videos for each Subject

In [2]:
data=pd.read_csv("./data/EEG data.csv", header=None)

names={0: "Subject ID", 1: "Video ID",2:"Attention",3:"Mediation",4:"Raw",5: "Delta",6:" Theta",7: "Alpha 1",8: "Alpha 2",9: "Beta 1", 10: "Beta 2" ,11: "Gamma 1", 12: "Gamma 2",13: "predefined label", 14: "user-defined label"}
data=data.rename(columns=names)

data=data.groupby(["Subject ID", "Video ID"]).mean()

3. Predictor distributions and correlations¶

In [10]:
features =["Delta"," Theta", "Alpha 1", "Alpha 2", "Beta 1", "Beta 2" , "Gamma 1", "Gamma 2"]
X=data[features]
skew=X.skew(axis=0)
# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, axes = plt.subplots(2,4, figsize=(20, 10), sharex=False)
sns.despine(left=True)
for ax,feature in zip(axes.flatten(),features): 
    sns.distplot(data[feature].values, color="b", ax=ax)
    ax.set_title("skewness {0:.2f}".format(skew[feature]))
plt.setp(axes, yticks=[]);
plt.setp(axes, xticks=[]);

Let's apply Box-Cox correction to the features where skewness is larger than $\frac{2}{3}$.

In [11]:
print(skew)
for feature in list(skew[np.abs(skew)>2/3].index):
    X.loc[:,feature]=stats.boxcox(X.loc[:,feature].values)[0]

3. Basic linear regression¶

I decided to add linear regression line with 95% confidence interval.

In [15]:
features = ["Delta"," Theta", "Alpha 1", "Alpha 2", "Beta 1", "Beta 2" , "Gamma 1", "Gamma 2"]
targets = ["Attention", "Mediation"]
f, axes = plt.subplots(8, 2, figsize=(20, 30), sharex=False)
for i,feature in enumerate(features):
    for j,target in enumerate(targets):
            sns.regplot(x=feature, y=target, data=data,ax=axes[i,j])
In [38]:
linear_model=LinearRegression(normalize=True)

# I get numply arrays of from DataFrames 
X=data[features].values
y_att=data["Attention"].values
y_med=data["Mediation"].values
In [39]:
y=y_att
linear_model.fit(X,y)
y_hat=linear_model.predict(X)
RMSE=(((y-y_hat)**2).mean())**(1/2)
print("RMSE for attention {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))

RMSE for attention 7.55
In [40]:
y=y_med
linear_model.fit(X,y)
y_hat=linear_model.predict(X)
RMSE=(((y-y_hat)**2).mean())**(1/2)
print("RMSE for mediation {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))

RMSE for mediation 4.92

Let's add some interactions $x_6 \cdot x_0$, $x_6 \cdot x_2$ ,$x_6 \cdot x_4$ and $x_i^2$

In [41]:
X=data[features].values
X=np.c_[X,X**2, X[:,6]*X[:,0],X[:,6]*X[:,2],X[:,6]*X[:,4]]
y=y_att
linear_model.fit(X,y)
y_hat=linear_model.predict(X)
data["Attention fitted"]=y_hat
data["Attention residuals"]=y-y_hat
RMSE=(((y-y_hat)**2).mean())**(1/2)
print("RMSE for attention {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))
y=y_med
linear_model.fit(X,y)
y_hat=linear_model.predict(X)
data["Mediation fitted"]=y_hat
data["Mediation residuals"]= y-y_hat
RMSE=(((y-y_hat)**2).mean())**(1/2)
print("RMSE for mediation {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))

RMSE for attention 6.83
RMSE for mediation 4.44

5. Linear regression for prediction¶

In [44]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
In [66]:
X=data[features].values
X=np.c_[X,X**2, X[:,6]*X[:,0],X[:,6]*X[:,2],X[:,6]*X[:,4]]
y=y_att
scores = cross_val_score(linear_model, X, y, cv=5,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
RMSE=np.sqrt(-scores).mean()     
print("RMSE for attention {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))
y=y_med
scores = cross_val_score(linear_model, X, y, cv=5,scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
RMSE=np.sqrt(-scores).mean()  
print("RMSE for mediation {0:.2f}".format(RMSE))

RMSE for attention 15.12
RMSE for mediation 9.53

The RMSE is higher than it was when we looked at the whole dataset. It indicated that before we overfit to our data. So maybe we need to add regularisation
